         <abstract>
            <p>There is a widely held view in some financial circles that industrial development bonds--whereby municipalities and public industrial development boards sell bonds to construct plant facilities for lease to private business--are a most undesirable practice. The author contends that while there are legitimate disadvantages associated with such bonds, these are neither sufficient nor important enough to warrant discontinuing their use. It is suggested that the meritorious aspects of IDB's be examined and recast to place a more proper emphasis upon their role in local economic development. Experiences of aggressive users of IDB's indicate that they have contributed heavily to inexpensive and successful efforts towards raising living standards in low income areas. It is concluded that the social benefits of industrial development bonds outweigh their disadvantages by an impressive margin.</p>
          </abstract>
